Why This Is Asked
- Tests end-to-end event-driven design, basic NLP steps (language detection, sentiment, key phrases), and translation in a beginner AWS context.
- Checks data privacy choices (encryption, access control) and cost-conscious retry strategy.

Key Concepts
- Event-driven Lambda orchestration, Comprehend detects language + sentiment + key phrases, Translate for non-English text, SSE-KMS for storage, DynamoDB upsert
- IAM least privilege, DLQ for failed items, and limits to small JSON sizes

Code Example
```javascript
// Node.js: Lambda handler sketch
const AWS = require('aws-sdk');
const s3 = new AWS.S3();
const comprehend = new AWS.Comprehend();
const translate = new AWS.Translate();

exports.handler = async (e) => {
  const key = e.Records[0].s3.object.key;
  const obj = await s3.getObject({Bucket: 'feedback', Key: key}).promise();
  const text = obj.Body.toString();
  const lang = (await comprehend.detectDominantLanguage({Text: text}).promise()).Languages[0].LanguageCode;
  let enText = text;
  if (lang !== 'en') {
    enText = (await translate.translateText({Text: text, SourceLanguageCode: lang, TargetLanguageCode: 'en'}).promise()).TranslatedText;
  }
  const sentiment = (await comprehend.detectSentiment({Text: enText, LanguageCode: 'en'}).promise()).Sentiment;
  const phrases = (await comprehend.detectKeyPhrases({Text: enText, LanguageCode: 'en'}).promise()).KeyPhrases.map(p=>p.Text);
  // write both originals and translation, and upsert DynamoDB (omitted for brevity)
};
```

